  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>In a Finnish cohort of 227,866 people with alcohol use disorder, followed for a median of 8.8 years, semaglutide outperformed every medication currently approved for that condition. Not by a little. Lähteenvuo and colleagues, publishing in JAMA Psychiatry in 2025, found an adjusted hazard ratio of 0.64 for AUD hospitalization — a 36% risk reduction that exceeded the effect sizes of acamprosate, naltrexone, and disulfiram, the three drugs that have anchored alcohol use disorder pharmacotherapy for decades. The dataset was large enough to be taken seriously. The methodology was rigorous enough to be published in one of the field's most selective journals. The finding was, by any reasonable standard, remarkable.</p>
  <p>Now hold that finding in one hand. In the other, hold this: a propensity-score matched cohort of 162,253 patients with obesity, published in Scientific Reports in 2024, found that GLP-1 receptor agonist treatment was associated with a 98% increased risk of any psychiatric disorder, a 195% higher risk of major depression, and a 108% increased risk of anxiety. Same class of drug. Different dataset, equally large. Equally peer-reviewed.</p>
  <p>Both findings are real. Neither is fully explained. And the field is not currently equipped to reconcile them.</p>
  <p>This is not a story about a miracle drug. It is not a story about a dangerous drug. It is a story about what happens when a pharmacological agent acts on the brain's most fundamental architecture — the systems that govern reward, craving, stress, and emotional experience — and the science trying to understand it is running several years behind the prescriptions already being written.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-addiction-signal" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Addiction Signal Is Real, and It Is Strong</h2>
  <p>Start with what the evidence actually supports, because the addiction data are, by the standards of this field, unusually consistent. Qeadan and colleagues, analyzing over 1.3 million patient records in the journal Addiction in 2024, found that people with opioid use disorder taking GLP-1 drugs had a 40% lower rate of opioid overdose compared to non-users. Those with alcohol use disorder had a 50% lower rate of alcohol intoxication. These are not marginal signals buried in confidence intervals. They are large, clinically meaningful differences in hard outcomes — overdose, intoxication, hospitalization — not self-reported craving scores.</p>
  <p>A separate Nature Communications analysis of over 800,000 insurance records found significantly lower rates of alcohol use disorder diagnoses among GLP-1 receptor agonist users compared to those taking other diabetes medications. The Finnish JAMA Psychiatry cohort added the hospitalization data. A 2025 phase 2 RCT by Hendershot and colleagues at the University of Southern California found that low-dose semaglutide significantly reduced laboratory alcohol self-administration (β = -0.48, P=.01), drinks per drinking day, and weekly alcohol craving versus placebo over nine weeks, with medium-to-large effect sizes. The same trial found reductions in cigarettes per day among participants who smoked, suggesting the effect is not alcohol-specific. Over 30 animal studies have demonstrated reduced self-administration of alcohol, opioids, nicotine, and cocaine with GLP-1 receptor agonists. The preclinical literature is, by the standards of addiction neuroscience, unusually convergent.</p>
  <p>Dr. Lorenzo Leggio at the National Institute on Drug Abuse has been direct about the interpretation: "We believe that these medications are active in the brain and, similar to their actions on food, they also curb craving for addictive drugs." Dr. Lähteenvuo's team, writing in JAMA Psychiatry, called for clinical trials "urgently," noting the effect was larger than that of officially approved AUD medications. That is a striking sentence from researchers trained to be cautious.</p>

  <aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The Finnish cohort found an adjusted hazard ratio of 0.64 for AUD hospitalization — a 36% risk reduction that exceeded the effect sizes of acamprosate, naltrexone, and disulfiram combined."</p></aside>

  <p>But the evidentiary hierarchy matters here, and it must be respected. The Hendershot RCT — the only randomized controlled trial of semaglutide specifically for alcohol use disorder — enrolled 48 participants and ran for nine weeks. It did not show significant reductions in total drinking days or average drinks per calendar day, which are the outcomes clinicians actually care about most. The Finnish cohort, for all its size, is observational. The Addiction journal analysis is observational. Observational data in GLP-1 research carries a specific and serious methodological problem: healthy-user bias. Patients who access these drugs — which remain expensive, often poorly covered by insurance, and associated with motivated health-seeking behavior — are systematically different from those who don't. They are more likely to be engaged with healthcare, more likely to be reducing substance use for other reasons, more likely to have social and economic resources that independently predict better outcomes. This is not a minor caveat. It is a structural problem that cannot be fully resolved by propensity-score matching, and it must be named explicitly when interpreting every positive observational finding in this literature.</p>
  <p>The exenatide precedent is instructive. Exenatide, the first GLP-1 receptor agonist tested in an RCT for alcohol use disorder, showed no significant effect on alcohol consumption in its primary analysis. The animal models had been compelling. The mechanism was plausible. The RCT did not deliver. Semaglutide may be different — it is more potent, more CNS-penetrant, and the early RCT data are more encouraging — but the field has been here before.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-mechanism" class="reveal">
  <h2>Why the Brain Cares About a Gut Hormone</h2>
  <p>The mechanistic story is genuinely compelling, and it deserves precision rather than hand-waving. GLP-1 — glucagon-like peptide-1 — is synthesized peripherally by intestinal L-cells in response to food intake, but also centrally by preproglucagon neurons in the nucleus tractus solitarius of the brainstem, which project directly into limbic and reward circuitry. GLP-1 receptors are expressed in the hippocampus, amygdala, prefrontal cortex, nucleus accumbens, and ventral tegmental area. That last pair — the nucleus accumbens and VTA — is the core of the mesolimbic dopamine system, the circuit that assigns motivational salience to stimuli and drives the compulsive seeking behavior that defines addiction.</p>
  <p>When semaglutide binds to GLP-1 receptors in the VTA and nucleus accumbens, it attenuates dopamine-mediated reward signaling. The hedonic pull of a stimulus — food, alcohol, opioids, nicotine — is reduced. The drug doesn't eliminate the stimulus; it turns down the volume on how much the brain cares about it. This is exactly why it reduces food intake, and it is exactly why it appears to reduce drug craving. The mechanism is not speculative. It is supported by receptor mapping, by preclinical pharmacology, and by the pattern of effects observed across multiple substance classes in animal models.</p>
  <p>GLP-1 signaling also modulates corticotropin-releasing hormone neurons in the paraventricular nucleus of the hypothalamus, implicating the HPA axis — the body's primary stress-response system. It promotes hippocampal neurogenesis and synaptic plasticity. It modulates serotonin, dopamine, GABA, and glutamate release. It reduces neuroinflammation and microglial activity. A comprehensive analysis in Nature Mental Health in 2025, reviewing 278 preclinical and mechanistic studies alongside 96 clinical studies, concluded that GLP-1 receptor agonists "act on bodily systems involved in the physiopathology of various neurological and psychiatric disorders" — a deliberately broad conclusion that reflects how many systems this drug is touching simultaneously.</p>

  <div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
    <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">GLP-1 Receptors in the Brain: Where They Are and What They Do</h4>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
      <li><strong>Nucleus Accumbens:</strong> Core reward processing; GLP-1 activation dampens dopamine-mediated motivational salience — the mechanism most likely driving addiction reduction</li>
      <li><strong>Ventral Tegmental Area (VTA):</strong> Origin of mesolimbic dopamine projections; GLP-1 signaling attenuates reward-circuit activation by addictive substances</li>
      <li><strong>Amygdala:</strong> Fear, stress, and emotional memory processing; implicated in anxiety effects and stress-induced relapse</li>
      <li><strong>Hippocampus:</strong> Memory consolidation and neurogenesis; GLP-1 activation promotes synaptic plasticity and may counteract depression-related atrophy</li>
      <li><strong>Prefrontal Cortex:</strong> Executive function and impulse control; modulated via dopaminergic and glutamatergic pathways</li>
      <li><strong>Paraventricular Nucleus:</strong> HPA axis regulation via CRH neurons; links GLP-1 signaling to the body's core stress-response architecture</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>Here is the problem, stated plainly: the same mechanism that makes this drug promising for addiction is the mechanism that might make it harmful for mood. A reward system tuned down for alcohol craving is also a reward system tuned down for the pleasure of a meal with friends, the satisfaction of finishing a project, the emotional resonance of music. Dr. Anna Lembke, the Stanford addiction specialist and author of <em>Dopamine Nation</em>, has raised this concern directly, warning that "dampening the reward system broadly could be problematic for people in addiction recovery who need to find healthy sources of pleasure." That is not a fringe position. It is a mechanistically coherent concern from someone who understands both the neuroscience and the clinical reality of what recovery actually requires.</p>
  <p>Addiction recovery is not simply the absence of drug use. It is the reconstruction of a capacity for pleasure, meaning, and connection that addiction has eroded. A drug that broadly attenuates reward salience may be working against that reconstruction in ways that current clinical trials — measuring drinks per day and craving scores over nine weeks — are not designed to detect.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-psychiatric-harm-signal" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Depression Signal Cannot Be Explained Away</h2>
  <p>The Scientific Reports finding deserves its full weight, not a paragraph of methodological hedging designed to make readers feel better. A propensity-score matched cohort of 162,253 patients found GLP-1 receptor agonist treatment associated with a 98% increased risk of any psychiatric disorder, a 195% higher risk of major depression, and a 108% increased risk of anxiety. These are not small signals. A nearly tripled risk of major depression, in a dataset of over 160,000 people, is not a rounding error.</p>
  <p>Methodological explanations have been proposed. The study population — patients with obesity — may have had higher baseline psychiatric vulnerability. The propensity-score matching may not have fully controlled for confounders. The ascertainment of psychiatric diagnoses in insurance records is imperfect. These are legitimate concerns. None of them fully resolve the finding. The researchers who proposed those explanations have not demonstrated that they account for the magnitude of the observed effect.</p>
  <p>The pharmacovigilance data add a separate and independent signal. A VigiBase analysis of 2,061,901 adverse drug reports found significant disproportionality signals for anxiety (adjusted reporting odds ratio 1.26), depressed mood disorders (aROR 1.70), and suicidality (aROR 1.45) specifically with semaglutide. Pharmacovigilance data are not clinical trial data — they capture reported adverse events, not controlled comparisons — but signals of this magnitude in a dataset of over two million reports are not dismissed without explanation. The European Medicines Agency opened a formal safety review. The Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency in the UK followed. The FDA investigated reports of suicidal ideation in 2023 and issued a preliminary evaluation suggesting no causal link, but the EMA review remains ongoing as of this writing.</p>

  <aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"A nearly tripled risk of major depression, in a dataset of over 160,000 people, is not a rounding error. Methodological explanations have been proposed. None of them fully resolve the finding."</p></aside>

  <p>Against this, the majority of the evidence points in the opposite direction. The eClinicalMedicine Lancet study, using electronic health records from over 100 million US patients, found no increased risk of anxiety or depression with semaglutide and a lower risk of cognitive impairment compared to other antidiabetic drugs. A post hoc analysis of the STEP 1, 2, 3, and 5 trials published in JAMA Internal Medicine in 2024 found a statistically significant reduction in depressive symptoms with semaglutide — though the estimated treatment difference of -0.56 on standard scales is, by any clinical standard, negligible. A 2024 meta-analysis in the American Journal of Geriatric Psychiatry found significant reductions in depression scale scores among GLP-1 receptor agonist users, while cautioning that improvement in diabetes symptoms may be a major confounding factor. The Swedish national cohort in Lancet Psychiatry 2026 suggested semaglutide "might be useful" for anxiety and depression co-occurring with diabetes and obesity.</p>
  <p>The majority of the evidence is more reassuring than the Scientific Reports outlier. But "majority of the evidence" is not the same as "resolved." The heterogeneity across these studies is extreme: different drugs, different doses, different patient populations, different outcome measures, different follow-up periods. A 2026 systematic review in Diabetes, Obesity and Metabolism concluded that GLP-1 receptor agonists show "modest antidepressant effects, inconsistent associations with suicidality, and potential therapeutic benefit in disorders of reward regulation" — and then, in the same sentence, noted that findings are "constrained by limited sample diversity and underrepresentation of individuals with psychiatric illness." That last clause is the one that should stop readers cold.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-exclusion-scandal" class="reveal">
  <h2>The People Left Out of Every Study</h2>
  <p>Virtually every psychiatric study of GLP-1 receptor agonists has systematically excluded people with serious mental illness. Schizophrenia. Bipolar disorder. Severe treatment-resistant depression. Active suicidality. These are the patients who carry the highest burden of metabolic disease — antipsychotic medications cause weight gain and metabolic dysregulation at rates that make the general obesity epidemic look modest — and who might therefore have the most to gain from a drug that addresses both metabolic and psychiatric pathology simultaneously. They are also the patients most likely to be harmed by an agent that disrupts reward and stress-response architecture in ways we do not yet understand.</p>
  <p>They are not in the data. They have been excluded from the evidence base that physicians are now using to make prescribing decisions. Roger S. McIntyre at the University of Toronto, writing in Expert Opinion on Pharmacotherapy in 2026, argued that GLP-1 receptor agonists "have potential to transform health outcomes for persons with bipolar disorder, schizophrenia, major depressive disorder and other serious mental illnesses by lengthening healthspan and reducing excess and premature mortality." That may be true. It may also be catastrophically wrong for a subset of those patients. We do not know, because those patients were not enrolled.</p>
  <p>This is not a minor methodological limitation. It is a structural failure of the clinical trial enterprise — one that reflects the longstanding tendency to treat psychiatric comorbidity as a reason for exclusion rather than a reason for inclusion. The population that most needs the answer is the population for whom we have no answer.</p>

  <aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The population most likely to benefit — and most likely to be harmed — has been systematically excluded from the evidence base. The people left out of every study are the people the question is actually about."</p></aside>

  <div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
    <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">The Evidentiary Hierarchy: What the Studies Actually Show</h4>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
      <li><strong>Strongest addiction signal:</strong> Finnish JAMA Psychiatry cohort (n=227,866, 8.8-year follow-up); Addiction journal analysis (n=1.3M records) — large, consistent, but observational and subject to healthy-user bias</li>
      <li><strong>Only addiction RCT:</strong> Hendershot et al., JAMA Psychiatry 2025 (n=48, 9 weeks) — significant on secondary endpoints, not on primary clinical outcomes; underpowered for definitive conclusions</li>
      <li><strong>Strongest harm signal:</strong> Scientific Reports cohort (n=162,253) — 98% increased psychiatric disorder risk; unexplained, unresolved, not replicated but not refuted</li>
      <li><strong>Pharmacovigilance:</strong> VigiBase (n=2,061,901 adverse drug reports) — elevated signals for depression (aROR 1.70) and suicidality (aROR 1.45); hypothesis-generating, not confirmatory</li>
      <li><strong>Regulatory status:</strong> EMA safety review ongoing; FDA preliminary evaluation found no causal link to suicidality; MHRA monitoring active</li>
      <li><strong>Critical gap:</strong> Zero RCT evidence in patients with serious mental illness; zero long-term psychiatric safety data beyond 12 months in high-risk populations</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="the-contradiction" class="reveal">
  <h2>Two Real Findings, One Unexplained Drug</h2>
  <p>The addiction medicine implications and the mood disorder implications are not the same story, and flattening them into a single "mental health" claim does violence to both. The addiction signal is stronger, more consistent across study designs, more mechanistically coherent, and supported by convergent preclinical and clinical data across multiple substance classes. The mood disorder signal is weaker, more heterogeneous, more contested, and more confounded by the metabolic improvements that accompany weight loss and glycemic control. These are different questions with different evidentiary states.</p>
  <p>But they share a mechanism. And that is precisely what makes the contradiction so difficult to resolve. If semaglutide's psychiatric effects were mediated by weight loss alone — improved self-esteem, reduced inflammation, better sleep — then the addiction effects would be harder to explain, and the depression risk would be easier to dismiss as confounding. If the effects are mediated by direct action on mesolimbic dopamine circuitry — which the receptor distribution data and preclinical pharmacology strongly suggest — then both the addiction benefit and the depression risk become mechanistically coherent simultaneously. The drug may be doing exactly what the mechanism predicts: broadly attenuating reward salience, with consequences that are beneficial for compulsive drug-seeking and potentially harmful for the capacity to experience ordinary pleasure.</p>
  <p>That is not a paradox. It is a single mechanism with two faces. The problem is that we cannot currently predict which face a given patient will see, because we do not have the biomarkers, the genetic data, or the longitudinal psychiatric assessments to stratify risk. We do not know whether the depression risk is concentrated in patients with pre-existing vulnerability, or distributed across the population. We do not know whether it emerges at specific doses, or specific durations of treatment, or in specific neurobiological contexts. We do not know, because the studies that would answer those questions have not been done.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-clinical-reality" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Prescriptions Are Already Written</h2>
  <p>Physicians are prescribing semaglutide off-label for addiction right now. Not in clinical trials. Not under research protocols with psychiatric monitoring and informed consent documents that specify the evidentiary uncertainty. In ordinary clinical practice, to patients with opioid use disorder and alcohol use disorder, on the basis of observational data that cannot establish causation and a single underpowered RCT that did not hit its most important endpoints. Dr. Christian Hendershot, whose team conducted that RCT, has been explicit: "It's too soon to endorse off-label use for addiction. We need rigorous randomized controlled trials first." Dr. Anna Lembke has echoed the caution, calling for longer-term studies before widespread addiction use. There are currently 13 ongoing clinical trials of semaglutide for cognitive and neurological disorders, and the addiction trials are accumulating. The evidence is being generated. It is not yet here.</p>
  <p>Meanwhile, regulators are still investigating whether the drug causes psychiatric harm. The EMA review is open. The VigiBase signals have not been explained. The Scientific Reports cohort finding has not been replicated or refuted. The patients with serious mental illness who were excluded from every study are being prescribed this drug by clinicians who have no evidence base specific to their population.</p>
  <p>This is the honest condition of medicine at the edge of what it knows. A drug acting on the brain's core reward and stress architecture is generating simultaneously the most promising addiction signal in a generation and an unexplained psychiatric harm signal, and the clinical system is not waiting for the science to catch up. The gap between what we know and what we are doing is not a failure of individual physicians — it is the predictable consequence of a blockbuster drug moving faster than the research enterprise that is supposed to understand it.</p>
  <p>The Finnish cohort is real. The 98% increased depression risk is real. The mechanism is compelling and the uncertainty is genuine. Somewhere in the space between those facts, patients are making decisions and clinicians are writing prescriptions, and the science has not yet told us what we need to know to do either responsibly. That is where we are. That is where we will remain for some time.</p>
</section>

